data.title: Duolingo's Q4 sales beat estimates at $282.868 million but forecasts for FY2026 at $1.197-1.221 billion were lower than expected.
data.description: Duolingo Inc (DUOL) announced strong fourth-quarter sales of $282.868 million, surpassing market expectations of $275.925 million. However, their sales forecast for FY2026 falls below estimates, with expected revenues between $1.197 billion to $1.221 billion, compared to the projected $1.264 billion. The company highlighted the impact of AI advancements on learning methods and expressed a strategic shift towards prioritizing user growth and enhancing teaching quality. Duolingo aims to enhance the free learner experience to drive organic growth and expand into new sectors like chess, math, and music, which may temporarily impact financial growth. This shift positions Duolingo for future success. For more information, refer to the complete story on Benzinga.com.

data.title: Digital Realty Trust Inc Q4 earnings tested credit ratings, with S&P BBB+, Fitch BBB, Moody's Baa2. Revenue grew 13.9%, FFO/share up 7.5%, fee income doubled to $137.2M. Net debt-to-Adj. EBITDA 4.9x, issued $1.6B Eurobonds in Nov. fell to $0.24 in Q4 from $0.51 last year.
data.description: Digital Realty Trust Inc (NYSE: DLR) reported fourth-quarter results that highlight a discrepancy in credit ratings by different agencies. S&P rates the company at BBB+, while Fitch and Moody’s rate one notch lower at BBB and Baa2 respectively. Q4 results for Digital Realty showed positive growth with Core FFO per share reaching $1.86, a 7.5% increase over Q4 2024, bringing the full-year figure to $7.39, a 10.1% increase. Revenue grew by 13.9% to approximately $1.63 billion, driven by demand in hyperscale and enterprise segments. Fee income also doubled from $64.9 million in 2024 to $137.2 million in 2025, following an oversubscribed closed-end fund that attracted $3.225 billion in commitments. The company's balance sheet maintained health with a net debt-to-Adjusted EBITDA at 4.9x. In November, Digital Realty issued €1.4 billion of green Eurobonds and repaid €1.075 billion of senior notes in December. However, GAAP net income per share fell to $0.24 in Q4, with a $78.5 million impairment provision and elevated operating costs. Transaction and integration expenses totaled $36.1 million in the quarter. While S&P credits the company's capital diversification, increasing fee income, and leverage discipline, Fitch and Moody's take a more cautious stance due to the drop in net income and high AFFO payout ratio.

data.title: Google and OpenAI employees demand 'red lines' in Pentagon AI contracts, over 100 Google staff members signed a letter expressing concerns.
data.description: Employees at Alphabet's Google, listed as GOOGL and GOOG on NASDAQ, are voicing their concerns about the company's collaboration with the Pentagon on artificial intelligence technology. More than 100 Google employees wrote a letter to management outlining their worries and suggesting the implementation of clear boundaries or "red lines" for government contracts similar to those followed by Anthropic. The New York Times reported on Thursday that the employees are troubled by the potential use of Google's Gemini A.I. product by the U.S. military for surveilling American citizens and operating autonomous weapons without human oversight. The letter was directed to Jeff Dean, the chief scientist at Google's A.I. division, Google DeepMind. Dean has expressed support for Anthropic, a stance that conflicts with the employees' concerns. The complete story can be found on Benzinga.com.
